data-triple-N3.o: "De facto is a Latin expression that means "concerning fact. " In law, it often means "in practice but not necessarily ordained by law" or "in practice or actuality, but not officially established. " It is commonly used in contrast to de jure (which means "concerning the law") when referring to matters of law, governance, or technique that are found in the common experience as created or developed without or contrary to a regulation."@en
